[
    {
        "content": "<p>How are you defining algebraic groups, let alone their representations?</p>\n<p>I also need algebraic groups (over a general field, mostly affine ones) for FLT (and also finite group schemes over a general base).</p>",
        "id": 504444401,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741564179
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Channel for discussing implementation of algebraic groups and reps</p>",
        "id": 504592584,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741615592
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"#narrow/channel/487278-toric/topic/Algebraic.20groups.20and.20representations/near/504444401\">A message</a> was moved here from <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"487278\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/487278-toric/topic/Current.20tasks/with/501728686\">#toric &gt; Current tasks</a> by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"548696\">Michał Mrugała</span>.</p>",
        "id": 504592692,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1741615613
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was planning to define algebraic groups as group objects in the category of schemes (so <code>{G : Scheme} [Grp_Class G]</code>).</p>",
        "id": 504592902,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741615663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When it comes to representations the plan is to define it as a morphism of functors <code>G → GL V</code></p>",
        "id": 504593259,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741615736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm very open to suggestion on how to approach defining both of these though, especially since they should be useful for other people.</p>",
        "id": 504594571,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741615974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"548696\">Michał Mrugała</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/487278-toric/topic/Algebraic.20groups.20and.20representations/near/504592902\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I was planning to define algebraic groups as group objects in the category of schemes (so <code>{G : Scheme} [Grp_Class G]</code>).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That will only give you group schemes over Spec(Z). You don't want group varieties over e.g. a field?</p>",
        "id": 504656572,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741630262
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We’ve also defined them in the Over category as group objects</p>",
        "id": 504656717,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741630291
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"548696\">Michał Mrugała</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/487278-toric/topic/Algebraic.20groups.20and.20representations/near/504594571\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I'm very open to suggestion on how to approach defining both of these though, especially since they should be useful for other people.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I've definitely used infinite-dimensional representations before (the regular representation for example), but I'm trying to think how these could fit in your definition.</p>",
        "id": 505058334,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741767574
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For an arbitrary representation of <code>G</code> on <code>V</code>, you want every element of <code>V</code> to be contained in a <code>G</code>-stable finite type submodule.</p>",
        "id": 505059051,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741767771
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(So that it corresponds to a comodule structure on <code>V</code> over the Hopf algebra of <code>G</code>, when <code>G</code> is affine.)</p>",
        "id": 505059178,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741767807
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you want at least the elements of <code>GL V</code> to be locally finite automorphisms of <code>V</code>, i.e. automorphisms <code>g</code> of <code>V</code> such that every element of <code>V</code> is contained in a <code>g</code>-invariant submodule of finite type.</p>",
        "id": 505061039,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741768337
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I'm not sure that's enough to be able to define a group scheme structure on <code>GL V</code>. I want to say something like \"<code>GL V</code> should be the colimit over all decompositions <code>V = \\oplus V i</code> of <code>V</code> as a direct sum of finite type submodules of the product of the <code>GL (V i)</code> (maybe it's safer to make <code>V</code> projective too, I need to think about it more). We do want a property like that, but I find that definition ugly.</p>",
        "id": 505062100,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741768648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition I found in the literature : <code>GL V</code> is defined to be the group valued functor on the category of <code>R</code>-algebras mapping <code>A ↦ Aut_A(V ⊗ A)</code>. As far as I can tell this satisfies the conditions you outlined, but as far as I can tell <code>GL V</code> is not representable in general when V is infinite-dimensional.</p>",
        "id": 505143277,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741788376
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think that satisfies the condition you need for representations. For example, if <code>V</code> is the free <code>k</code>-vector space on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> and <code>g</code> acts by translation by <code>1</code> on basis elements, then it is an automorphism of <code>V</code> hence defines a <code>k</code>-point of your functor <code>GL V</code>, but it does not stabilize any finite-dimensional subspace of <code>V</code>, so we don't want a group scheme to act on <code>V</code> through that element.</p>",
        "id": 505211613,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741802854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Your functor <code>GL V</code> is almost certainly not representable by a scheme if <code>V</code> is infinite-dimensional, but neither is the functor I suggested, I think. The difference is that the functor I suggested is an inductive limit of schemes, i.e. an ind-schemes, and these are still reasonably well-behaved.</p>",
        "id": 505212080,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741802966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In order to define morphisms from <code>G</code> to <code>GL V</code>, we don't need <code>GL V</code> to be representable anyway, because we can just take morphisms of sheaves in groups, and by Yoneda this will give the correct result for <code>V</code> finite-dimensional, where there is no doubt what the definition of <code>GL V</code> should be.</p>",
        "id": 505212361,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741803033
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The thing is, I never saw a definition via \"morphism into <code>GL V</code>\" in the literature for general representations, because, as you pointed out, with the classical definition of <code>GL V</code> it won't give the right notion in the infinite-dimensional case (which is definitely important). The only definition in that generality I saw is for affine group schemes and goes through the Hopf algebra.<br>\n<em>However</em>, this does not mean that such a definition is not possible/desirable, just that we have to be careful about <code>GL V</code> should be.</p>",
        "id": 505213300,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741803265
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, no, it's fine! If <code>G</code> is an <em>affine</em> group scheme, then using the definition of <code>GL V</code> that you suggest will lead to the correct notion of representation, though that is not totally obvious. Whew! (I keep forgetting that the discrete group scheme <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> is not affine...)</p>",
        "id": 505219645,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741804825
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great! I was starting to get worried. In any case I should track down how they're defined in SGA3 to compare.</p>",
        "id": 505227419,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Mrugała",
        "timestamp": 1741806951
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My guess is that they define a representation of a group scheme <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> (where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> is a commutative ring) on a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>-module <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> as an action of the functor in groups <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto G(A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> on the functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>M</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>k</mi></msub><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto M\\otimes_k A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> (where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is a commutative <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span>-algebra) that preserves the linear structure on each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>k</mi></msub><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M\\otimes_k A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 505230518,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Morel",
        "timestamp": 1741807821
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which is equivalent to a morphisms of functors in groups from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto G(A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mi>A</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>k</mi></msub><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto\\mathrm{Aut}_A(M\\otimes_k A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Aut</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">A</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
